<subSubSection pageId="2" pageNumber="386" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph blockId="2.[151,1437,541,926]" pageId="2" pageNumber="386">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[151,266,541,566]" pageId="2" pageNumber="386">Diagnosis</emphasis>
. At this time, 
<taxonomicName authority="Shear &amp; Shelley, 2019" authorityName="Shear &amp; Shelley" authorityYear="2019" box="[425,587,541,565]" class="Diplopoda" family="Macrosternodesmidae" genus="Packardesmus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Polydesmida" pageId="2" pageNumber="384" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus" status="n. gen.">
<emphasis box="[425,587,541,565]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="386">Packardesmus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is the only known North American polydesmidan genus in which the males have 18 trunk rings (females have 19 rings); a few polydesmidan species with 18-ringed males are found in 
<collectingCountry box="[151,239,613,638]" name="Mexico" pageId="2" pageNumber="386">Mexico</collectingCountry>
, the West Indies and elsewhere. In addition, the gonopods have a unique, hand-like appearance (with only four fingers; 
<figureCitation box="[300,406,649,674]" captionStart="FIGURES 1–7" captionStartId="4.[151,264,1884,1906]" captionTargetBox="[150,1436,195,1828]" captionTargetId="figure@4.[150,1436,195,1860]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="FIGURES 1–7. Packardesmus cavicola. Fig. 1. Head, antennae, collum and first three rings of male, ventrolateral view. Fig. 2. Head, collum and first four rings of male, dorsal view. Fig. 3. Rings 12 and 13 of male, dorsal view. Fig. 4. Gonopods, ventral view. Fig. 5. Right gonopod, posteroventral view. Fig. 6. Apex of left gonopod, ventral view; s, solenomere, p, pore. Fig. 7. Gonopods, posterior view." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/2626946/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="386">Figs. 4–7</figureCitation>
) due to the elongated femoral region of the gonopod and the basal fusion of the branches; only the solenomere branch (
<emphasis bold="true" box="[481,492,686,709]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="386">s</emphasis>
, 
<figureCitation box="[507,574,685,710]" captionStart="FIGURES 1–7" captionStartId="4.[151,264,1884,1906]" captionTargetBox="[150,1436,195,1828]" captionTargetId="figure@4.[150,1436,195,1860]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="FIGURES 1–7. Packardesmus cavicola. Fig. 1. Head, antennae, collum and first three rings of male, ventrolateral view. Fig. 2. Head, collum and first four rings of male, dorsal view. Fig. 3. Rings 12 and 13 of male, dorsal view. Fig. 4. Gonopods, ventral view. Fig. 5. Right gonopod, posteroventral view. Fig. 6. Apex of left gonopod, ventral view; s, solenomere, p, pore. Fig. 7. Gonopods, posterior view." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/2626946/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="386">Fig. 6</figureCitation>
) can be confidently homologized with the branches of the gonopod in other macrosternodesmid genera due to this fusion. Other characters as described for the 
<typeStatus box="[1099,1201,721,746]" pageId="2" pageNumber="386">lectotype</typeStatus>
and newly collected material.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="2" pageNumber="386" type="distribution">
<paragraph blockId="2.[151,1437,541,926]" pageId="2" pageNumber="386">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,345,793,818]" pageId="2" pageNumber="386">Distribution</emphasis>
. Known only from the 
<typeStatus box="[626,674,794,818]" pageId="2" pageNumber="386">type</typeStatus>
locality of the single included species, but possibly more widely distributed.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="2" pageNumber="386" type="etymology">
<paragraph blockId="2.[151,1437,541,926]" pageId="2" pageNumber="386">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,327,865,890]" pageId="2" pageNumber="386">Etymology</emphasis>
. Named for pioneering speleobiologist A. S. Packard, with the combining stem – 
<emphasis box="[1284,1367,865,889]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="386">desmus</emphasis>
, used frequently for polydesmidan millipedes.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
